  <!-- Section: Common Mistakes -->
  <section id="mistakes" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Missing the 8-Day Permesso Deadline</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">You must apply for your permesso di soggiorno within 8 days of arriving in Italy. This is strictly enforced. Go to a post office immediately—don't wait to "settle in" first.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Not Securing Accommodation First</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">You need proof of Italian accommodation before applying for the visa. This often means signing a lease remotely or visiting Italy to secure housing before your visa application.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Underestimating Bureaucracy</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Italian bureaucracy is notorious. Offices have limited hours, appointments are required, and processes take time. Build extra time into every step and maintain pazienza (patience).</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Missing the 7% Tax Opportunity</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Italy offers a 7% flat tax on foreign income for retirees who settle in qualifying southern regions. Research this before choosing where to live—the savings can be substantial.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Assuming English Will Suffice</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Outside tourist areas, English is limited. For bureaucratic appointments, doctors, and daily life, you'll need Italian. Start learning before you move—it dramatically improves quality of life.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Healthcare in Italy -->
  <section id="healthcare" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Healthcare in Italy</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Italy's healthcare system (Servizio Sanitario Nazionale - SSN) ranks well internationally. After establishing residency, you can voluntarily join the public system by paying an annual fee. Many retirees use a combination of public and private care.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Public vs. Private Healthcare</h3>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
      <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Public (SSN)</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-neutral-700">
          <li>• <strong>Access:</strong> Voluntary registration (~€400/year)</li>
          <li>• <strong>Coverage:</strong> Comprehensive, low/no cost</li>
          <li>• <strong>Quality:</strong> Good, varies by region</li>
          <li>• <strong>Wait times:</strong> Can be long for specialists</li>
          <li>• <strong>Language:</strong> Italian primarily</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Private</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-neutral-700">
          <li>• <strong>Access:</strong> With private insurance</li>
          <li>• <strong>Cost:</strong> €150-400+/month</li>
          <li>• <strong>Quality:</strong> Excellent</li>
          <li>• <strong>Wait times:</strong> Short</li>
          <li>• <strong>Language:</strong> English available in major cities</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Regional Variation</h3>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Healthcare quality in Italy varies significantly by region. Northern regions (Lombardy, Emilia-Romagna, Veneto) generally have better public facilities. Southern regions have improved but may have longer waits. Private healthcare is excellent throughout.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Sample Costs (Private, Without Insurance)</h3>

    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
      <li><strong>GP visit:</strong> €80-150</li>
      <li><strong>Specialist:</strong> €100-200</li>
      <li><strong>Emergency room:</strong> €150-400</li>
      <li><strong>Dental cleaning:</strong> €60-100</li>
      <li><strong>MRI:</strong> €200-500</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What is the 7% flat tax for retirees?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Italy offers a 7% flat tax on all foreign income for retirees who move to qualifying southern regions (populations under 20,000) or certain southern provinces. This applies for 10 years and can result in significant tax savings.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How do I join the public healthcare system?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          After getting your permesso di soggiorno, visit your local ASL (health authority) office to register for voluntary SSN coverage. You'll pay approximately €400/year (subject to change) and receive a tessera sanitaria (health card).
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I need to speak Italian?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Not for the visa, but strongly recommended for quality of life. Outside major tourist areas, English is limited. For healthcare, bureaucracy, and daily interactions, Italian is essential. Start learning before you move.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How long until citizenship?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Italy requires 10 years of legal residency for citizenship (4 years for EU citizens). However, if you have Italian ancestry, you may qualify for citizenship by descent (jure sanguinis)—a much faster path.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I buy property with this visa?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes. Non-residents can buy property in Italy (subject to reciprocity with your home country—fine for US/UK/EU citizens). Property ownership can strengthen your visa application and provide your accommodation proof.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What's the Codice Fiscale?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          The Codice Fiscale is Italy's tax identification number. You need it for almost everything—opening a bank account, signing a lease, getting utilities. You can obtain it at the Italian consulate or at the Agenzia delle Entrate in Italy.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

